Rating: 4
Like many others, I made this dish for a small dinner party on a cold (California) winter night. It was fantastic. I have to weigh in on this "saucy or dry" issue. First of all, I grew up in an immigrant Italian family and I am well on the record among my friends for not liking saucy dishes and I know that these baked pasta dishes especially are not intended to be saucy - which is part of why I love them. Having said that, after I had added all the ingredients, I came across a small jar of gourmet crushed tomatoes from Italy in my pantry and I could not resist adding it. I'm glad I did -- it was perfect. I must say, I used a little more pasta though. One of my guests was a professional athlete (who is notorious for eating large quantities) and he had 4 helpings (big ones.) My friend's husband (a lanky fellow) had 3 and the rest of us had 2 each plus, my friend reported gobbling up the leftovers with her 5 year old for lunch the next day. I served it with a simple spinach braised with olive oil and garlic, a warm "take and bake" Pain Rustic from LaBrea Bakery, a hearty Tuscan Red and a chocolate/hazelnut gelato with cooled espresso over the top. I too had leftovers today with the last glass of the wine and it was divine. I actually warmed it in the microwave because it had become a little too dry in the fridge and the moisture was the perfect touch although my mother used to actually reheat these dishes in a fry pan over medium heat with just a touch of olive oil in the pan -- that's how prone to the slightly drier, slightly crunchy the Italians are. I would also make sure you get it out of the oven right at 20 minutes and I recommend searing the pork aggressively to lock in the moisture and flavor. It is a great "putter around the house project." I made the sauce the night before and simmered gently for another hour during reheat.

