Rating: 3
This ragu sauce is extremely good, and I would definitely make it again. I divided the recipe half to make 4 servings. The changes I made for my 1/2 recipe were: subbed 2 oz. Louis Rich low-fat chopped and formed turkey bacon, subbed 6 oz. (by weight) pre-cooked pork sirloin roast, subbed 2 links (4.5 oz. total) of Hillshire Farm beef hot links, subbed 1/2 tsp. dried thyme, added 1/2 tsp. of Italian seasoning, subbed dry white wine, subbed a 14.5 oz. can of Italian diced tomatoes, subbed penne pasta and reduced it to 8 oz., and mixed a bit of ricotta cheese with the mozzarella and parmesan cheeses. I divided the mixture between two 8-1/2 by 4-1/2 inch glass bread loaf pans, baked one and froze the other (without any cheese). Even though I had pre-cooked pork and sausage, it still took me 1-3/4 hours to get this in the oven, but I did start from scratch with chopping the veggies, pork, and sausage, shredding the cheeses, etc. Next time I would use lean boneless country ribs (as suggested), and simmer it for 2 hours with extra diced tomatoes, as my pre-cooked sirloin was too lean, therefore it remained very dry.

